<https://w3id.org/pink#Material> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#Entity> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Material> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "The class of individuals standing for an amount of matter (ordinary, anti or hybrid) substance (or mixture of substances) in different states of matter or phases."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Material> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Material"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#MaterialProcess
<https://w3id.org/pink#MaterialProcess> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#MaterialProcess> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#Process> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#MaterialProcess> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "A process that has material as input and output."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#MaterialProcess> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "MaterialProcess"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#MaterialProcess> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#skopeNote> "Since MaterialProcess is a subclass of Process, we say that there must exist a method that describes the material process." .
# 
# https://w3id.org/pink#Measurement
<https://w3id.org/pink#Measurement> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Measurement> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#subClassOf> <https://w3id.org/pink#Process> .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Measurement> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition> "An observation that results in a quantitative comparison of a 'property' of an 'object' with a standard reference based on a well defined mesurement procedure."@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Measurement> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Measurement"@en .
<https://w3id.org/pink#Measurement> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#skopeNote> "Since Measurement is a subclass of Process, we say that there must exist a method that describes the measurement." .
